## USER RESEARCH

*(Sources: beauty community forums, TikTok creator comment patterns, Quora threads, beautyheaven.com.au community discussion, nail tech educator content, WhoWhatWear reader FAQs, Joyee Nails community Q&A — Reddit inaccessible, triangulated from all available community sources)*

### Top 5 Pain Points (Real, Current)

1. **"I don't know if almond will suit me specifically"** — The most pervasive anxiety. Users know what almond nails look like; they do not know if their hand shape, nail bed width, or finger length makes them a good or bad candidate. They see the style on influencers with very specific hands and wonder if they'll look the same. Generic "flatters everyone" answers do not satisfy this — they want hand-specific logic.

2. **"My almond nails always break at the tip"** — High-frequency complaint from both natural nail wearers and enhancement clients. Users don't understand why breakage happens at the tip specifically (stress point geometry, over-filing the sidewalls, wrong application method). They want practical prevention, not just "be careful." This is especially acute for those transitioning from square or squoval.

3. **"I have short nails — is almond even possible for me?"** — Strong confusion around the minimum length requirement. Many readers assume almond is only for long nails and rule themselves out. The emergence of "baby almond" and short almond as legitimate 2026 sub-styles is not yet mainstream knowledge outside NailTok.

4. **"I don't know which product system to get — acrylic, gel, or BIAB"** — Readers who want almond nails face a decision tree they feel unqualified to navigate. They know these options exist but don't understand which is best for *the almond shape specifically*. Community discussion shows frequent confusion between what each system can structurally achieve (BIAB for shorter almond, acrylic/hard gel/Gel-X for dramatic length).

5. **"Almond nails seem high-maintenance — is the upkeep really worth it?"** — Practical concern from women with active lifestyles (those who use hands a lot: keyboards, gym, cooking, childcare). They are drawn to the look but worried about breakage and fill frequency. The "almonds are harder to maintain than oval" narrative is pervasive in community discussions and creates hesitation. They want honest cost-benefit logic, not just aesthetic cheerleading.

### User Sentiment
Aspirational but anxious — readers are genuinely excited about the shape but held back by practical uncertainty about fit, durability, and product decisions. Many feel the information available is either too basic or too salesy to actually help them decide.

